H0.text: Dry ice is solid carbon dioxide.

H1.text: Carbohydrate is the name for solid carbon dioxide.

H2.text: Liquid nitrogen is solid carbon dioxide.

H3.text: Blue ice is solid carbon dioxide.

A4.text: Dry ice is the solid form of carbon dioxide (CO2), a molecule consisting of a single carbon atom bonded to two oxygen atoms.

A5.text: Dry ice is the solid form of carbon dioxide. It is commonly used for temporary refrigeration as CO2 does not have a liquid state at normal atmospheric pressure and sublimes directly from the solid state to the gas state.
